MAVLink is a Messaging Protocol and Serial API for microcontrollers, and it's widely used for the communication between various devices, such as Arduino and Pixhawk. It can be used to send messages from the Arduino to the Pixhawk and, ultimately, to QGroundControl.

Here's an example of an Arduino code that uses MAVLink version 1 to send messages to a Pixhawk:
```cpp
#include <FastSerialSync.h>
#include <Q_hnav.h> // Pixhawk MAVLink protocol
#include < firmware/mavlink.h> // MAVLink protocol

#define PORT Serial1 // choice your port name

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  Serial1.begin(57600); // PixhawkSerialPpmPort or PixhawkSerialUartPort
  mavlink_system.sysid = 255;
  mavlink_system.compid = 1;
  mavlink_message_t msg;
  mavlink_message_initialise(&msg, 0, 255, 1, MAVLINK_MSG_ID_IDLE, MAV_TYPE_QUADROTOR);
  mavlink_status_t status;
  mavlink_msg_to_send_buffer(255, 1, &msg);
  quakenet_set_id( wings.sysid, arm.system_id, 255, 1, &status);
}

void loop() {
  // sending MAVLink message
  mavlink_message_terior_t terr;
  mavlink_message_t msg;
  uint8_t buffer[MAVLINK_MAX_PACKET_LEN];
  uint16_t len;
  int ret;
  mavlink_status_t status;

  mavlink_message_init( &msg, MAVLINK_MSG_ID_IDLE, 42, MAV_TYPE_QUADROTOR, 0);
  mavlink_msg_idle_pack (3, 1, 0, &msg, MAV_TYPE_QUADROTOR);

  len = round((float)strlen((char *)buffer)/3.0 + 7);
  mavlink_message_to_send_buffer((uint8_t)MAV_TYPE_QUADROTOR, MAVLINK_MSG_ID_IDLE, &msg, (uint8_t*)buffer);

  ret = Serial1.write((uint8_t *)buffer,len);

  while (ret<len) {
    if(Serial1.available()>0) 
    {
      mavlink_status_t status;
      len = Serial1.read(buffer, MAVLINK_MAX_PACKET_LEN);

      ret = mavlink_parse_check(&status, &msg, (uint8_t*)buffer, len);
      if (ret > 0) {
        // your code here
      } else {
        // handle error here
      }
    }
  }
}
```
This code is an example of how you might send data from an Arduino to a Pixhawk using MAVLink version 1. It creates a MAVLink message and sends it over Serial1 (assuming you've connected the Arduino to the Pixhawk via a UART connection). The Arduino reads data from the Pixhawk and calls the MAVLink `parse_check` function to attempt to parse the received message. If the parsing is successful, you can process the received data as needed.

For the data to be sent to QGroundControl, you would need to configure the Pixhawk to send the data over a network connection (e.g., using Wi-Fi or a TCP/IP connection) and write code on the Pixhawk to send the data to QGroundControl. Once the Pixhawk sends the data to QGroundControl, QGroundControl will display it in the corresponding section of the user interface. You would need to modify the code in the Arduino to generate the data that you want to send to QGroundControl and ensure that the data is in the correct format for the specific feature in QGroundControl that you want to display it in.

